{"source_key":"sha256-365bf9c6581c5f98ab881132a14f970c","record_index":141,"record_hash":"sha256:d8bd94d84665bd3896b9da8d6019d4a3dab323f709fa43c7651b35c996fef9ce","timestamp":"2026-06-19T10:42:02.755Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"`GraphWorkspace.stacks` is the workspace projection’s grouping of commits that sit “below” the workspace commit.\n\nIn plain terms: it turns the editor’s step graph into stack-shaped chunks so callers can say, “these commits belong together as one stack,” instead of only seeing one big reachable subgraph.\n\nIn [workspace.rs]([REDACTED:path]), it’s used like this:\n\n- If you’re on `gitbutler/workspace` and a workspace commit is found:\n  - `above_workspace` gets commits above the workspace commit.\n  - `stacks` gets one subgraph per parent path under the workspace commit.\n- If no workspace commit is found:\n  - everything reachable from `HEAD ^target` is treated as `above_workspace`.\n  - `stacks` is empty.\n- If you’re not on the workspace branch:\n  - there’s no workspace commit split.\n  - `stacks` contains one stack: all commits in `HEAD ^target`.\n\nSo the property is basically for external/workspace callers that need a stack-oriented view of the rebase graph. It’s presentation/framing data, not a separate graph. Each stack is a `Subgraph` with `heads` and `nodes` as `Selector`s.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-19T10:42:02.755Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","metadata":{"turn_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"},"phase":"final_answer"}}}